did.abstract: The Robert Twining collection is comprised of photographs, scrapbooks, slides, negatives, and films of Camp Al-Gon-Quian. Located on Burt Lake, Michigan, the camp was founded in 1925 by Herbert H. Twining as a summer camp for boys. The materials in the collection detail activities of Camp Al-Gon-Quian, such as fishing, archery, and horseback riding. There are also materials relating to Camp Mississauga, which was a camp for older boys in Canada.

bioghist.p: The site that is now Camp Al-Gon-Quian was originally a farm on Burt Lake in Northern Michigan, just east of Petoskey. In 1925, Herbert H. Twining purchased the land with the intent to start a summer camp. Twining was a University of Michigan graduate (1923), who initially wanted to be a medical doctor. However, an eye injury as a child prevented this and instead Twining pursued a profession that he found to be similar: establishing a private boys' camp on the leading edge of camp programming.

Twining chose the name Al-Gon-Quian because he believed that was a possible Native American expression for "bow of a canoe." Twining also borrowed several Native American names for the camper groups. He divided the campers into groups by age, grade, height and weight. Throughout the years, the tribes within the camp included the Ottawa, Chippewa, Cree, Ojibwa, Miami, Nipissing and Mississauga. One common element that joined these native tribes together is that they were a part of the Algonquian linguistic family and spoke Algonquian when together.

In 1925, Twining opened camp for its first season. Sessions lasted 8 weeks, and boys came from all over Michigan and surrounding states. It was a popular summertime activity for prominent families from the Ann Arbor community and the Midwest. Well known attendees include: the Proctor & Gamble sons of Cincinnati, the Wrigleys of Chicago, the Strohs of Detroit and Grosse Pointe, and the children of University of Michigan figures Alvin Bentley, C.S. Mott and G. Mennen Williams. Prominent members of the university community that served as staff members include Bennie Oosterbaan, Dr. Roger Howell, Roscoe Bonisteel, E. Blythe Stason and James B. Edmonson.

In addition to providing a fun outdoor experience for campers, Camp Al-Gon-Quian aimed to improve the character of young men. In 1932, the aims of camp were to develop strength of character, a purpose in life, a clear moral character, self-reliance and the ability to achieve. This was accomplished through two months of camaraderie and living in the outdoors away from the stresses of city life.

Twining was well-recognized in the camping community and actively involved with the American Camp Association, of which he was the first national president in 1935. He was the director of Al-Gon-Quian for 42 years until his retirement in 1967, when he sold the camp to the Ann Arbor YMCA.

scopecontent.p: The collection contains two series: Photographs and Film.

Photographs (5 linear feet) are organized by subject. Almost all of the photographs and slides in the series are black and white. Most of the photographs are group photos, which are formal and informal group shots of the campers. Staff group photos can be found in the "staff" folder. A bulk of the series consists of water sports (swimming, sailing, canoeing), horseback riding, sports (rifle shooting, archery, tennis), other activities (educational and social), and daily activities (eating in dining hall, visiting nurse, getting haircuts). Most of the photographs are undated. In Box 4, there is a folder entitled, "photos in envelopes," which are photos of various activities that were labeled in envelopes. A small number of the photos do not seem to be related to the camp, but may be photos of Robert Twining's family. These photos are found in the unidentified folder.

In addition to seven scrapbooks with photos about camp life and travels in Ontario, Canada, Box 5 includes one folder with a brochure advertising the camp and one folder that contains loose notes. Four of the scrapbooks have labels with information such as names, date, and location. This box also contains the alphabetical and chronological lists of campers and counselors prepared in 2012 Camp Al-Gon-Quian Camper and Counselor files, 1925-1967.

The series also contains slides (4.5 linear feet). Box 6 contains loose slides that were stored in labeled envelopes. There are also loose slides that include an index to slide contents. The rest of the slides are ordered by the same subjects that the photographs are sorted by. There are a large amount of undated slides, but many contain descriptions. Box 8 contains slides that are in boxes with descriptive information. There is one box of 35 mm glass slides that should be handled with caution.

Finally, the series contains a box of photo negatives (.5 linear feet). These negatives have been arranged by subject to mirror the same organization as the photographs. Some of the negatives include their corresponding photograph.

scopecontent.p: The Film series (2 linear feet) contains 20 reels of 16 mm film recording activities of Camp Al-Gon-Quian. Some of the films are described on the box, but many contain no description. They date from 1930-1951.
